Using highcharter package to do stock plot

Yao Dou

3/9/2018

Highcharter is a wrapper R wrapper or Highcharts javascript library. The reason that I use this package to do stock plotting is because it has connection with quantmod package, which is a Quantitative Financial Modelling Framework. Highcharter has a function that you can pass the stock data which is downloaded by quantmod.

Simple plot

Here is the example to plot Amazon stock:

## library(highcharter)
## library(quantmod)
## auto.assign = FALSE means that it will not create an object called AMZN by itself
x <- getSymbols("AMZN", auto.assign = FALSE)
hc <- hchart(x)

or you can use this:

x <- getSymbols("AMZN", auto.assign = FALSE)
hc <- highchart(type = "stock") %>%
  hc_add_series(x)

You can set the type of the plot like column, candlestick, line, spline, area and etc Default plot type is candlestick

Here is an example which plot in spline:

highchart(type = "stock") %>%
  hc_add_series(x, type = "spline")

Add indicator

We can also add indicators to the plot such as Simple Moving Average, Bollinger Bands and Commodity Channel Index. Here is an example which add Bollinger Bands to the plot:

highchart(type = "stock") %>%
  hc_add_series(x) %>%
  hc_add_series(name = "Bollinger Bands", BBands(Cl(x)))

Add another stock to do comparison

Adding another stock to the plot is not hard. The code is similar to adding indicator part

y <- getSymbols("MSFT", auto.assign = FALSE)
highchart(type = "stock") %>%
  hc_add_series(x) %>%
  hc_add_series(y)

Add a menu bar in the right upper corner, where you can export the chart

hc %>%
  hc_exporting(enabled = TRUE)
